  "prompt": "Why do I have to tip the server?",
  "response": "Tipping servers is a common practice in many cultures, particularly in the United States, and it serves several purposes:\n\n1. **Wage Structure**: In many places, servers receive a lower base wage than the standard minimum wage because tips are expected to make up the difference. Tipping helps ensure that servers earn a livable income.\n\n2. **Service Incentive**: Tips are often seen as a reward for good service. They incentivize servers to provide better customer service, as a higher tip can result from a positive dining experience.\n\n3. **Cultural Norm**: Tipping has become a social norm in many countries, and not tipping can be seen as rude or disrespectful. Following this norm can help avoid awkwardness in social situations.\n\n4. **Personal Experience**: Customers may feel that tipping allows them to express their satisfaction with the service they received and fosters a direct connection between their experience and the compensation the server receives.\n\n5. **Industry Practices**: Many restaurants rely on tips to supplement their servers' incomes and maintain lower menu prices. This practice has been entrenched in the hospitality industry for a long time.\n\nWhile tipping is customary in many places, attitudes toward it can vary. Some people argue for a more standardized wage system for servers that doesn\u2019t rely on tips. Ultimately, whether to tip and how much is often a personal decision influenced by the quality of service and cultural expectations.",
